"1523–1615","1530–1583":"1530–1583","1482–Female":"1482–Deceased","Abt 1508":"about 1508","1583":"1583","1550":"1550","1482":"1482","1480":"1480","1558":"1558","15 October 1530":"15 October 1530","1523":"1523","1577":"1577","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","1530":"1530","1509":"1509","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1615":"1615","1559":"1559","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Frittenden, Kent, England":"Frittenden, Kent, England","Saint Mary's Church, Frittenden, Tunbridge Wells district, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"St Mary's Church, Frittenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Scott","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (Down): habitational and ethnic name from Middle English <i>Scot</i> ‘man from Scotland’. There is no evidence that the surname denoted either of the earlier senses of <i>Scot</i> as ‘(Gaelic-speaking) Irishman’ or ‘man from Alba’, the Gaelic-speaking region of Scotland north of the river Forth. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","English and Scottish: from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Scot</i> (Old English <i>Scott</i>, possibly also Old Norse <i>Skotr</i>), only certainly attested in northern England.","English: variant of   Scutt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Scutt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Pierre.","Americanized form of Dutch   Schutte   ‘archer’.","English: nickname for a short person, from Middle English <i>scut(e)</i> ‘short’, or else for a swift runner, from Middle English <i>scut</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: Bitter; Marion is the French form."],"variants":[{"name":"Marion","meanings":["Originally a medieval French diminutive form of   Marie  , introduced to Britain in the Middle Ages. In some places it was taken as a pet form of   Margaret   or   Margery .  As a male name, it is an altered form of the Continental male name <i>Marian</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>Marianus</i> (from   Marius  ), but is now rarely, if ever, used. It was the birth name of the American film star  John Wayne  (  1907–79 )."]},{"name":"Marcia","meanings":["Often used as a feminine equivalent of   Mark  , but in fact a feminine form of <i>Marcius</i>, itself a derivative of   Marcus .  One  St Marcia  is commemorated in a group with Felix, Luciolus, Fortunatus, and others; another with Zenais, Cyria, and Valeria; and a third with Ariston, Crescentian, Eutychian, Urban, Vitalis, Justus, Felicissimus, Felix, and Symphorosa. None is individually very famous."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":67,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":76,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":103,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":105,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700